<p><b>Bret Easton Ellis</b> (born March 7, 1964 in <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles,_California" title="Los Angeles, California" class="mw-redirect">Los Angeles, California</a>) is an American <a href="/wiki/Novelist" title="Novelist" class="mw-redirect">novelist</a> and <a href="/wiki/Short_story" title="Short story">short story</a> writer. He was regarded as one of the so-called literary <a href="/wiki/Brat_Pack_(literary)" title="Brat Pack (literary)">Brat Pack</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-bratpack_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bratpack-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> which also included <a href="/wiki/Tama_Janowitz" title="Tama Janowitz">Tama Janowitz</a> and <a href="/wiki/Jay_McInerney" title="Jay McInerney">Jay McInerney</a>. He is a self-proclaimed "moralist."<sup id="cite_ref-moralist_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-moralist-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Ellis employs a technique of linking novels with common, recurring characters.</p>
